## Block Design

### HTML structure

Use a scoped custom element wrapper for JavaScript attachment:

```html
<all-products-{id}
  data-default-sort="{{ block.settings.default_sort }}"
  class="all-products-{id} color-{{ block.settings.color_scheme }} {{ section_width }}"
  {{ block.shopify_attributes }}
>
  <!-- Sort buttons (conditionally rendered) -->
  <div class="all-products__sort">
    <button class="all-products__sort-btn" data-sort="price-asc">...</button>
    ...
  </div>

  <!-- Product grid -->
  <div class="all-products__grid all-products__grid-{id}" data-all-products-grid>
    <!-- For each product -->
    <div class="all-products__card"
         data-price="{{ product.price }}"
         data-name="{{ product.title | downcase | escape }}">
      <a href="{{ product.url }}" class="all-products__card-link">...</a>
      <!-- image, title, price -->
    </div>
  </div>
</all-products-{id}>
```

Use `{% assign id = block.id | replace: '_', '' | downcase %}` for scoped IDs.

### CSS strategy

- `{% style %}` — dynamic CSS using Liquid (grid columns, gaps, padding-block). Scoped to `.all-products__grid-{id}` and `.all-products-{id}`.
- `{% stylesheet %}` — static CSS for sort buttons, card layout, image, title, price. No Liquid.

### JavaScript

Use `<script>` (not `{% javascript %}`) since Liquid interpolation is needed for the custom element name and default sort value.

**Custom element `AllProducts{id}`:**
- On `connectedCallback`: cache product elements (price from `data-price`, name from `data-name`), bind sort button click listeners, apply `data-default-sort` immediately.
- `sort(key)`: re-append product elements in sorted order; toggle `.is-active` on buttons.

### Product card rendering

Inline rendering (not via `snippets/product-card.liquid`, which requires a full block context with per-card settings). Cards use simple CSS classes scoped to the block.

